00:02:46.237 --> 00:02:53.337
Money is a store of value, and this money can be exchanged for stuff.

00:02:53.857 --> 00:02:59.627
The company you work for pays you money because you do valuable work for them,

00:03:00.177 --> 00:03:05.037
you pay someone else money because they might do something that you consider

00:03:05.037 --> 00:03:10.817
valuable like serve you a coffee or sell you a newspaper or make podcasts for you.

00:03:11.687 --> 00:03:14.997
That’s the basic idea of how money works.

00:03:16.287 --> 00:03:21.017
Throughout history, different things were used to represent money.

00:03:21.727 --> 00:03:25.357
Different societies used different ways of representing

00:03:25.377 --> 00:03:30.067
it, from shells, to silver, and of course, gold.

00:03:31.387 --> 00:03:36.227
But using physical objects, especially metal like gold,

00:03:36.857 --> 00:03:40.657
wasn’t a very good way of storing or exchanging value.

00:03:41.507 --> 00:03:46.147
It’s heavy, it’s not easy to transport, and it's just

00:03:46.147 --> 00:03:50.437
not very practical to be used as a medium of exchange.

00:03:51.197 --> 00:03:54.167
So, the paper banknote was invented.

00:03:55.487 --> 00:04:01.537
The idea here was that you could store your gold in a bank, and the bank would

00:04:01.577 --> 00:04:07.637
give a note that you could pass to other people in exchange for goods or services.

00:04:08.737 --> 00:04:15.777
Technically, you could go to the bank and get the gold, but if you just wanted to do things

00:04:15.817 --> 00:04:21.767
like buy food, there was no need to, because you knew that you could give that note to

00:04:21.767 --> 00:04:27.397
someone else in exchange for more stuff, you didn't need to go and get the gold from the bank.

00:04:28.347 --> 00:04:32.617
The whole system worked because people knew that the gold did

00:04:32.617 --> 00:04:35.517
exist in the bank, they could go and get it if they wanted.

00:04:36.877 --> 00:04:44.307
But from 1971, paper money was no longer linked to gold, and instead,

00:04:44.537 --> 00:04:50.017
the government effectively guaranteed the value of your paper money.

00:04:50.787 --> 00:04:55.387
There was nothing physical behind the paper money, you just had

00:04:55.397 --> 00:04:59.327
to trust that the paper money would keep its value in the future.

00:05:00.327 --> 00:05:03.147
The world had essentially transitioned to a system

00:05:03.377 --> 00:05:05.997
where money was controlled by the central government.

00:05:06.727 --> 00:05:13.537
Your paper money doesn’t have any intrinsic value, its only value is because you know

00:05:13.537 --> 00:05:18.657
that everyone else agrees that it’s valuable, and the whole system works like that.

00:05:20.157 --> 00:05:26.147
The advantage of this system for a government is that, because there is nothing behind the

00:05:26.147 --> 00:05:33.347
paper money, it’s easy to create more of it, to add more money to the economy and pay for stuff.

00:05:34.627 --> 00:05:40.697
Although printing money sounds nice in principle, the more money that exists

00:05:40.947 --> 00:05:47.437
in a financial system, the less value each unit of money actually has.

00:05:48.597 --> 00:05:54.697
When prices rise due to inflation, this isn’t because prices naturally

00:05:54.697 --> 00:06:00.007
rise, it's because there is more money in the system, so each bit of

00:06:00.017 --> 00:06:03.947
money that we have in the system is worth less and less every year.

00:06:04.967 --> 00:06:10.837
And there are plenty of instances throughout history of governments printing too much

00:06:10.837 --> 00:06:16.647
money too quickly, there being more and more money in the financial system so that

00:06:16.687 --> 00:06:22.607
each unit of money is worth less, and the situation quickly spirals out of control.

00:06:23.857 --> 00:06:28.367
The obvious examples one would point at would be things like Germany

00:06:28.487 --> 00:06:34.237
in the 1920s, Zimbabwe in the 2000s, or Venezuela in more recent years.

00:06:35.087 --> 00:06:42.287
But even in the UK in 1975 inflation was at 25%, meaning

00:06:42.497 --> 00:06:46.967
that your money would be worth 25% less in 12 months time.

00:06:48.109 --> 00:06:53.443
But this episode isn’t just about money, the point is that governments control the

00:06:53.443 --> 00:06:58.283
supply of money, and people have to trust the government to do the right thing.

00:06:59.203 --> 00:07:03.443
And governments don’t always have a great track record at doing this.

00:07:04.323 --> 00:07:07.583
But it’s not just the government that you have to trust.

00:07:07.883 --> 00:07:09.853
You also have to trust the banks.

00:07:10.573 --> 00:07:15.833
The implicit deal that you make, when you put money in a bank, is that the

00:07:15.843 --> 00:07:20.553
bank will keep it safe, and it will allow you to make payments with it.

00:07:21.203 --> 00:07:26.603
And again, banks don’t have a fantastic track record at keeping your money safe.

00:07:27.603 --> 00:07:32.383
So banks control your money on a daily basis, while the

00:07:32.583 --> 00:07:36.103
government controls the total amount of money in the system.

00:07:36.953 --> 00:07:43.163
If you use Euros, dollars, or any other what’s called a ‘fiat’ currency,

00:07:43.373 --> 00:07:48.563
a currency that isn’t backed by anything like gold, you rely on this

00:07:48.593 --> 00:07:53.063
combination of the government and banks to keep everything ticking over.

00:07:54.283 --> 00:07:59.653
But from financial crashes to fraud to mismanagement, neither

00:07:59.693 --> 00:08:05.113
governments nor banks have that great a history at doing the right thing.

00:08:06.323 --> 00:08:12.003
So, this is the backstory, a little very quick intro to the complicated

00:08:12.013 --> 00:08:17.143
world of financial systems that all rely on one thing: trust.

00:08:18.343 --> 00:08:24.983
Just over 10 years ago a new idea emerged about how money could work that

00:08:25.033 --> 00:08:30.763
proposed a radically different way of thinking about the issue of trust.

00:08:32.263 --> 00:08:39.303
In 2009, someone with the pseudonym of Satoshi Nakamoto published a white paper,

00:08:39.403 --> 00:08:46.043
a document, introducing this new idea, a new type of money that didn’t require any

00:08:46.053 --> 00:08:52.073
banks or governments, that could be sent by anyone in the world to anyone else in

00:08:52.073 --> 00:08:58.473
the world, that aimed to solve a lot of the problems that exist with modern money.

00:08:59.803 --> 00:09:02.333
The name of the invention was Bitcoin.

00:09:03.783 --> 00:09:06.183
Bitcoin works on a few principles.

00:09:06.723 --> 00:09:08.893
Firstly, there is no physical bitcoin.

00:09:09.423 --> 00:09:14.013
It’s a cryptocurrency, so it only exists as computer code.

00:09:14.923 --> 00:09:21.403
It's what’s called ‘open source’, so anyone can see the computer code that controls it.

00:09:22.073 --> 00:09:28.393
Nobody ‘owns’ the bitcoin network, anyone who owns a bitcoin owns part of

00:09:28.393 --> 00:09:32.873
it, but there isn’t a central system, it’s what’s called decentralised.

00:09:33.363 --> 00:09:40.943
If you own bitcoin, you store it in a bitcoin wallet, which is a piece of software

00:09:40.963 --> 00:09:47.423
on your computer or mobile phone and contains a unique set of numbers and letters.

00:09:48.123 --> 00:09:52.843
That’s your bitcoin wallet’s address, and in there is your bitcoin.

00:09:54.223 --> 00:09:59.773
When it comes to making a payment in bitcoin, a crucial difference here versus

00:10:00.103 --> 00:10:05.073
normal money is that you don’t need any kind of bank to make the transfer.

00:10:06.233 --> 00:10:12.153
With a normal transfer or payment in Euros or dollars, your money goes through all

00:10:12.153 --> 00:10:17.753
sorts of different providers and banks before it actually reaches the other person.

00:10:18.883 --> 00:10:23.433
With Bitcoin, it goes straight from your bitcoin wallet to their

00:10:24.213 --> 00:10:29.403
bitcoin wallet, and the information about this transaction is added to

00:10:29.403 --> 00:10:34.323
a public record of every bitcoin transaction that has ever been made.

00:10:35.113 --> 00:10:36.583
This is called the blockchain.

00:10:36.583 --> 00:10:45.193
This chain is basically like a huge record of who has paid what, to whom, when.

00:10:46.683 --> 00:10:53.543
Unlike with a bank, it isn’t kept locked up in some large building, it exists on

00:10:53.563 --> 00:10:59.243
thousands of different computers all over the world, and is public, anyone can see it.

00:11:00.473 --> 00:11:05.203
Whenever a new bitcoin transaction is made, one of the computers in the

00:11:05.203 --> 00:11:10.993
network will verify that transaction and then add it to the public record.

00:11:12.013 --> 00:11:17.183
When it’s added to the record, other computers will check that the record

00:11:17.213 --> 00:11:22.413
is still the same, that no changes have been made, and then it is added.

00:11:23.653 --> 00:11:28.763
You can’t see who actually owns each bitcoin, but you can

00:11:28.763 --> 00:11:32.873
see the bitcoin address of who sent it and who received it.

00:11:34.243 --> 00:11:39.253
The advantage of everything being public and unable to be changed

00:11:39.273 --> 00:11:43.653
is that you can’t ever have a situation where a payment is made

00:11:43.703 --> 00:11:48.123
twice, or money is taken from your account without your permission.

00:11:49.463 --> 00:11:53.593
Similarly, you can’t wake up and find that a bank has taken your

00:11:53.593 --> 00:11:58.253
money, because the bank doesn’t control the account, you do.

00:11:59.493 --> 00:12:05.873
So, although many people might feel very strange about having money in a computer, money

00:12:06.123 --> 00:12:12.863
that they can’t feel or touch, and with no bank that they can go to, no nice person they can

00:12:12.863 --> 00:12:18.163
phone up and certainly no statements coming through their letterbox every month, bitcoin’s

00:12:18.783 --> 00:12:26.953
advocates propose it as a much safer, more secure way to store money, to store value.

00:12:28.463 --> 00:12:34.733
The final, perhaps most important reason that Bitcoin has so many fans is

00:12:34.773 --> 00:12:39.983
because there are only a fixed number of bitcoins that can ever be produced.

00:12:41.113 --> 00:12:46.193
Specifically, there are only 21 million bitcoins that can ever exist.

00:12:47.673 --> 00:12:53.393
If you remember the start of the episode when I mentioned inflation and governments

00:12:53.493 --> 00:12:59.823
printing money, the reason that having a fixed number of bitcoins is important is

00:12:59.913 --> 00:13:06.193
because bitcoin can’t be affected by inflation in the same way was as fiat currency.

00:13:07.533 --> 00:13:13.993
Inflation only exists when new money is added to the supply, and because

00:13:14.033 --> 00:13:19.673
the supply of bitcoins that will ever exist is fixed, this can’t happen.

