that it’s not yet practical to be used to buy and sell anything at any date

00:17:13.391 --> 00:17:19.451
in the future - it’s only ever sort of practical to make purchases right now.

00:17:20.601 --> 00:17:24.981
So that’s why you might see places like Starbucks accepting

00:17:24.991 --> 00:17:29.941
bitcoin, but it’s not so common to see houses for sale in bitcoin.

00:17:30.492 --> 00:17:35.232
While some governments are embracing cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin, saying

00:17:35.442 --> 00:17:39.802
that they will be the future of money, others are trying to clamp down on them.

00:17:40.582 --> 00:17:45.742
Being in control of the money supply is a very important thing for any government,

00:17:46.162 --> 00:17:50.932
which means you can put money into the economy in the short term, for example

00:17:51.152 --> 00:17:54.632
if there’s a devastating pandemic and you need to stimulate the economy.

00:17:55.602 --> 00:18:00.992
If everyone in a country uses a currency that isn’t controlled by that country’s

00:18:01.002 --> 00:18:06.382
government, then the government can’t print money, it can’t easily raise money

00:18:06.382 --> 00:18:11.542
to pay for things, and that has got a lot of countries’ governments very scared.

00:18:12.772 --> 00:18:15.962
And the country that is perhaps the most scared of Bitcoin?

00:18:17.082 --> 00:18:18.102
The United States.

00:18:18.852 --> 00:18:22.812
The US is particularly afraid of what Bitcoin could become

00:18:23.042 --> 00:18:27.122
because the US has the world’s reserve currency, the dollar.

